AUTHOR: abrom8
CONTENT: dear @ğŸ§‘â€ğŸ’»builder     deltadao has released the first public version of nautilus  an ocean.js wrapper. it's open-source and has been released under apache-2.0 license.  **key features of nautilus include:**  - simple installation via npm  allowing users to get started in minutes - builder classes that eliminate the need to learn ddo structures - easy publishing of datasets and algorithms for access and compute - support for starting compute jobs and retrieving results - consumption of access type assets (datasets & algorithms) - support for userdata and algocustomdata parameters - extensive readme with ready-to-go usage examples   **feel free to test  provide feedback and contribute on github:**  https://github.com/deltadao/nautilus  https://www.npmjs.com/package/@deltadao/nautilus

AUTHOR: white_rider_
CONTENT: details on this:  veocean does use vyper  but is not affected by the  bug.   ocean core team has been in touch with the vyper team to get more info.  ocean uses vyper in these contracts: veocean  vedelegation  vefeedistributor  vedelegationproxy  and vefeeestimate.  only vedelegationproxy uses a vulnerable version of vyper.  however  the reentrancy lock is not used  and there are no external eth calls.   so  it's safe.

CONTENT: @oceandiffusion create an artwork inspired by the natural habitat of leafeon  the grass-type eeveelution  deep inside a lush forest. imagine yourself walking through a dense forest  surrounded by towering trees  verdant foliage  and the sounds of nature. suddenly  you catch sight of a leafeon  camouflaged amidst the greenery. the creature stands gracefully  its emerald eyes glinting in the sunlight filtering through the trees. as you watch  leafeon nimbly jumps from one branch to another  moving with effortless grace through its natural habitat.  in your artwork  capture the beauty and serenity of this moment. use vibrant greens and earthy browns to convey the rich colors of the forest  and add a sense of depth and texture to the foliage and tree trunks. pay close attention to the details of leafeon's appearance and movements  from the sharp contours of its fur to the fluidity of its jumps. finally  imbue your artwork with a sense of tranquility and harmony  reflecting the delicate balance of nature in which leafeon plays a vital role.

AUTHOR: wally0221
CONTENT: here is the basic idea of turning the new and rising idea of using nfts as log-in into a web3 data supply and demand hook  and how we could leverage for v4 data nft also. it remains a fragment  as it was publicly on twitter.   it ends with a question: how to connect a) and b)  accomplishing i)-iv)?  the answer i didn't give in the thread  but is is clear imo  is: use data nfts (and datatoken) to bridge the gap.  as in: turn current nfts into data nfts (easiest v1 hack by trent: just mint and add a data nft on ocean market into the same wallet as the og nft  perform "validation" of legitimacy by checking if both nfts are in the same address  also re: @realdatawhale our talk).   apply all possible web3 newdataeconomy functionality from data nft per user and/or union (datatoken  apis  data streams  etc.  your magic): https://twitter.com/cryptowally2/status/1520057298361671682?s=20&t=74rsqhrytr6y2yj_c8wmha

AUTHOR: wally0221
CONTENT: last part is longer down the road and really experimental  but it basically inverts the process outlined in concept 1. and 2. and allows members of pfpclubs to start their own data selling business  be it around their data pool  or completely different data points (like qr codes  tickets  physical collectibles verified e.g. via wiseart  etc). this is not relevant first step  but eventually relevant for your conceptual thoughts down the road:  https://twitter.com/cryptowally2/status/1520057929558376450

AUTHOR: mantisclone
CONTENT: > unlimited use of training data for a period of time this is possible using datatokens and wouldn't require the data nft owner to relinquish control of the data nft. when creating the datatoken  specify the `timeout` to be the number of seconds that a given order is valid for. the dataset or algorithm can then be consumed or used for compute-to-data as many times as the consumer wants until the timeout is reached.  > or to try monetize the data on your behalf? i could imagine a professional service that runs ocean infrastructure on behalf of a data publisher. this would certainly require some off-chain coordination and trust  but could still be accomplished using datatokens. the datatoken's `service_endpoint` could point to a provider instance run by the ocean infrastructure provider.  the infrastructure provider would collect provider fees while the data nft owner collects order fees.

AUTHOR: Timothy.AthenaProtocol.Eth#2384
CONTENT: i thought i'd come by and share something pretty exciting that we have been working on over the past few months.   athena protocol is a member organization and founder of dmeter  a dao for the creation of open standards in mrv ( monitoring reporting and verification ) for esg. this organization has begun to develop its system of governance of these open standards  and athena protocol is leading the engineering circle  helping to bring adoption of ocean protocol tools and softwares. our work creating signed claims and comments for the ocean stack has prepared us to compose our middleware's into a data transaction and verification layer capable of conducting audits and certifying ecosystem services. we have a list of organizations planing to integrate with our middleware.   one organization im very excited to announce in particular participating in the integrations is the regen network ! they will be modifying their attestations to accept ipfs hashes  as well as working with us to develop a shared meta-data schema for v2 of our contracts.  v2 will include geospatial indicators for data assets for easy spatial searches and more!

AUTHOR: swish24_08
CONTENT: basically c2d pairs some datasets with an algorithm so that the user never sees the raw data just what the algorithm generates. ideally you review the algorithms that are allowed on your dataset so that it doesn't just return it. this can work with static datasets and you can team up with someone that creates the algorithm so that both of you can profit. the best use case is with dynamic data (that updates constantly) so the user need to start a c2d job each week or each month depending on how fast the data updates.

CONTENT: i'm not sure i fully understand what you are trying to do here? barge deploys the ocean contracts on ganache and then starts up the other ocean components in docker containers. when you say  "connect to a different ethereum rpc provider" it sounds like you are trying to use a different network?   if your intention is to use a different testnet  i would highly recommend that you use one of the testnets that we are already deployed to - such as goeli or mumbai. barge is not a tool for deploying the contracts to other networks. normally all contract deployments are handled by the core team.

AUTHOR: carmina19
CONTENT: hello @alex  if you use barge  the contracts are deployed locally on ganache/development network and you need to export the address file (because for ganache the addresses are not persistent) like this `export address_file=~/.ocean/ocean-contracts/artifacts/address.json`. if you want to use a remote network  you do not need barge.

AUTHOR: white_rider_
CONTENT: it's not necessarily the case. when the url points to an endpoint that retrieves data  updates can occur even if the asset's metadata remains the same.

AUTHOR: white_rider_
CONTENT: so for example  with a graphql published asset  you won't need to modify the asset's metadata to access updated data. when a query is sent to your server  the server can retrieve the most recent data based on the specific query and parameters without the need for metadata changes. this flexibility allows for efficient and dynamic data retrieval while keeping the asset's metadata unchanged.

AUTHOR: idiom_bytes
CONTENT: yeah  i generally agree. as i mentioned previously alerts and actionable intelligence can be fairly premium.  what i would argue is that not all alerts and not all intelligence is premium.  example: a stream of stakes  buys  etc... is not very actionable.  imbalances between dcv and staked amounts are because this is where users can harvest most yield.  in the presentation i provided you  i have alluded to how to build a freemium model that converts users from free  into paying  by slowly increasing the friction and guiding them towards monetization.  example of a previous arbitrage tg app... -------- i made most buys/sells alert free. you could access many bot commands that helped users stay engaged and discover the app.  this facilitated the onboarding of thousands of users (no initial friction  more daily active users)  and keep them engaged (more user sessions).  however  alerts on arbitrage spreads (i.e. buy on dex1 and sell on dex2 for 5%) and other features were premium because this is where users make money.  this enabled me to obtain many more users (larger funnel due to no friction)  while providing them towards a clear path of monetization (obvious value offering/conversion).  many freemium products offer multiple skus (i.e. multiple token gates within a single freemium app). each token gate (sku) can be linked to a different feature/super power.  this is where understanding your users segments (different users  different goals) and how to build premium features (solving the customer problem for each segment) within a single freemium product  can lead to much larger revenue.  hope this helps.

AUTHOR: Norbert | Ocean#7805
CONTENT: hello @jon77777 . you are right  now the easiest way to see if a dataset is a good quality one is to check the last rounds apy and predict that it could work well on current round as well. beside that there could be other ways to understand the quality of the dataset: - look at the content of the dataset  is it a good one  does it have good demand in the future? - look at the publisher. if the dataset has been published by a trusted publisher and the publisher has other good datasets you can presume that the dataset is a good quality one and has more chances to be consumed. - be aware of wash consume. right now there is a wash consume game going on  if you try to understand or play that game  it will give you a better overview of where the rewards are going.

AUTHOR: Norbert | Ocean#7805

AUTHOR: idiom_bytes
CONTENT: hi damien   our base models are currently simple. only using linear regression  and a single timeframe that you specify... such as 1h timeframe.  **[overview of how slots/epochs work]** in this case  we're trying to predict the price at t+1  our dataframe/xy will look like this (1 hour slots/epochs). ``` timestamp  price 00:00:00  1000 00:01:00  1005.?? < this is happening now  so the 1h candle hasn't closed yet 00:02:00  t+1 < what we're predicting for ```  this means that 5m  15m  and 30m data is not included in the model building. **this also means that we can't wait for 00:01:00 to close  because we need to submit the prediction for 00:02:00 before the candle closes.**  the best thing you could do here without a lot of work  is to submit predictions for t+1 right before the candle closes  using the current (00:01:00) price.  **predictoor_agent3.py is already implemented to do this.** => https://discord.com/channels/612953348487905282/1184520151912165496/1184895704196468888

AUTHOR: idiom_bytes
CONTENT: hi damien  we're in the middle of re-writing a bunch of stuff  pardon me.  i think you're right that the current price is not included in hist_df because the candle hasn't closed yet  so it will not be included.  if you wanted to inject more granular candle data  (but this adds a lot of records  and increases the number of dimensions of your model making it more costly to train/etc...) is to create a dataframe that is composed of 1m + 5m data... whether this improves the performance of the model significantly or not... well  that's part of the exploratory work.  to exemplify this  here is a pseudo df where your implementation would consist of 11 columns: - 1 for timestamp - 5 for ohlcv 1m - 5 for ohlcv 5m  this way  you can a more complete representation of price in a dataframe ``` ts | ohlcv_1m_btc_binance | ohlcv_5m_btc_binance 1 | 1000 | 1000 2 | 1001 | 1000 3 | 1002 | 1000 4 | 1001 | 1000 5 | 1001 | 1000 << 5m candle closes here 6 | 1002 | 1001 << 5m columns would then start using the last 5m ohlcv candle  while 1m columns continue using historical 1m ohlcv candles ```  you are now in the realm of improving model performance  and there are 100 things you can work towards to improving it. rather than us guessing  there is a lot of literature on the subject. one of the best resources on it today is the book: "advances in financial machine learning 1st edition by marcos lopez de prado". i also recommend searching the web as there are many resources and libraries that build upon it.  lmk if you have more questions.

AUTHOR: idiom_bytes
CONTENT: consider the following 5m epochs ``` t0 < we are here t1 < next epoch t2 < epoch we're predicting for ```  your submissions will be made for epoch t2. once t0 closes  you will be unable to submit predictions for t2  as you'll now be submitting a prediction for t3.  ``` are there other ways to lose ocean besides losing predictions? because i have been thinking and figuring out but i should be in profit even though my balance is only decreasing ```  not quite... but it's important to understand the details... (as laid out in the docs/blogpost linked  by awesomeqa)  if you predict with 0.5 ocean  while others are predicting with 0.1 ocean  if you lose  you lose your whole stake... not 0.1. so  it's important to get a measure for how others are staking such that you're taking the right amount of risk.  we're working towards building more tooling around this such that it's easier for predictoors to monitor and improve their stake. tbd.

AUTHOR: idiom_bytes
CONTENT: 1. good  the latest prices are included. 2. the model/system we're building is designed to re-train/build/predict on the fly. please be mindful of this as training/deploying something on the cloud (or even locally) will change the behavior we're designing for.  this will evolve in the future... i.e. build/cache/re-use model for 10 epochs.  as you probably know  trained models can drift in performance  and managing ml models is a practice on its own.  3. the predictor agent has been designed to make multiple submissions in the last 60s.  why? - each prediction will have different data as p1 will have the latest_price up to the last 60s. then p2 will be up to the last 30s. finally p3 might have most of the last candle data  up-to-the very end of the epoch.  look at pdr_trader for how to cache/check if you've already submitted a prediction for an epoch if you only want to submit once... again  please be mindful of the example i gave above as to why we do this as the default behavior.  4. make sure that your bot submitted something first  then run the script against the right network and that your start/end times look good.  if you are still having issues  try running this subgraph query in our sapphire subgraph directly to see if you can find any of the predictions you have submitted for in the past: https://github.com/oceanprotocol/pdr-backend/blob/5c1a67796c680c610111cd238005f639d298d5f3/pdr_backend/util/subgraph_predictions.py#l23  again  double check that you are running the query against the right subgraph (testnet vs. mainnet)

AUTHOR: ndubss
CONTENT: running multiple predictoor bots in ocean protocol involves some limitations and complexities  but there are potential workarounds depending on your needs and risk tolerance. here's what you need to know:   challenges and limitations:  security: using multiple bots with the same wallet increases your attack surface  as each bot needs access to private keys and could potentially drain funds. this is the biggest concern. api key restrictions: depending on the platform you use to connect your bots  api key limitations might hinder running multiple bots simultaneously. exchange restrictions: some cryptocurrency exchanges impose limitations on the number of bots or api keys allowed per account. complexity: managing and coordinating multiple bots with different strategies can be challenging and susceptible to unintended consequences.  potential workarounds:  multiple wallets: this is the safest option  requiring separate wallets for each bot with unique private keys. however  managing multiple wallets effectively adds complexity and requires strong security practices. single bot with strategy switching: develop a single bot capable of switching between different prediction strategies based on defined parameters. this offers flexibility while maintaining control in one place. testnets and simulations: utilize platforms like ocean testnet or other simulations to test your bots and strategies without risking real funds. this is recommended before deploying bots on the mainnet. cloud providers and virtual machines: explore advanced setups using cloud providers like aws or azure to create isolated virtual machines for each bot  potentially improving security but requiring technical expertise.  disclaimer:  due to the inherent security risks  running multiple bots on the same wallet is generally not recommended. carefully consider the risks and legal implications in your region before using bots for trading. thoroughly research and understand the limitations and complexity involved before attempting any workaround. never share your private keys or seed phrases with any bot or program.

CONTENT: is there any platform for non-techy users to contribute to datasets or aggregate / annotate data?

AUTHOR: sarahsweetchilli
CONTENT: *example:* i'm a non-techy person with a lot of pictures on my phone and i want to make money from this data.   *another example* i am a person with spare time  who isn't familiar with ai or machine learning  and i want to make side money from data annotation or data generation (these are repetitive and simple jobs once the fundamentals are laid down)

AUTHOR: sarahsweetchilli
CONTENT: right now the people selling datasets are people who have already aggregated and annotated data. to my knowledge most of these people are business managers  crypto nerds or ai experts. nothing wrong with this  it's just a niche audience.

AUTHOR: sarahsweetchilli
CONTENT: ocean could appeal to the entire world  rather than just experts  if we make data annotation accessible & profitable for the average person. if we build dapps that allow normal people to upload + annotate data in their spare time and make a bit of cash whilst doing it--say  they can draw bounding boxes around pictures from their phones--we would increase ocean's fundamental value whilst creating casual jobs.

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: a few questions to help us help you - how long will the video be? i saw your previous video and from what i understand the platform you are using to create them is providing you with images/objects and effects to create the video  right?  what is ocean? this is covered well by the mission statement of ocean here: https://oceanprotocol.com/about  from my point of view the core components of ocean protocol have been created in the past - namely: marketplaces  compute-to-data and datatokens as well as the beginning of the oceandao. this can all be used to enhance data science. that are the achievements.  what is still outstanding from the technical point of view is the integration of compute-to-data into the marketplace itself. the only thing that is publicly know about it can be found in the roadmap of ocean: https://oceanprotocol.com/roadmap quote:  in ocean market: buy & sell private data while preserving privacy mitigates risk of buyer-supplied malicious algorithms  via whitelisted algorithms or workflow for publisher to vet algorithms  to me this means that data can be sold without having to leave the storage of the data provider. also that this data cannot be copied by the buyer. but that the compute done by the algorithms are also covered by the data provider via their hardware. and that the data buyer will pay for this compute.

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: hi everyone  scott here. iâ€™m excited to join and discover how i can best use my skillset to help build on oceanâ€™s vision. i work in product development/management and recently negotiated and implemented a $6.5m usd development contract with over 40 developers and designers.   iâ€™m eager to build products and am open to submitting a proposal for review but donâ€™t yet have a strong use case. iâ€™ve been speaking with @mark about the positioning/business strategy with ocean and keen to explore this topic in more detail. we collaborated on a question for the community below:

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: the objective of this question is to get a clear understanding of the unique value proposition of ocean so that we can better serve  and strategically implement ocean protocolâ€™s vision in the market.Â   as we understand  the ocean protocol is ultimately a 2 sided marketplace connecting buyers and sellers of data. one could have a popular dataset on an ocean market which generates $500 000 in revenue and another person may have 500 datasets on ocean market generating $0 in revenue based on the demand for their data assets.Â   itâ€™s possible (but unlikely) that i am going to receive a lot of money for sharing my personal location data. even in the best case scenario i may generate a few $100 dollars which some may find attractive but most will encounter too much friction/hesitation towards opening up and sharing their personal data for some relatively small sum of money. (this may not be the case in all situations/countries as a few hundred dollars will be a lot of money but in those cases the buying power of that consumer base would be lower and therefore the incentive for businesses to leverage that data would be lower also).

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: therefore  the higher value datasets for ocean are likely those held in big privately held databases or brokered in other partnering models like: www.datarade.ai which could:     1.    benefit from being used in machine learning algorithms  ai etc to create value (i.e. there is demand for the data).Â â€¨     2.    be sold to the market without the company receiving a significant backlash from existing customers/business partners/shareholders i.e. the benefits of enabling access to the data (revenues generated) outweigh the costs of providing secure access to the data for the market to consume. one could imagine a backlash against a local retailer if customers discovered that all of a sudden their shopping data was being sold by the retailer for profit.â€¨ this is where we start to get a little stuckâ€¦ if there is huge revenue potential sitting behind closed doors (in privately held databases)  then why wouldnâ€™t a more traditional private company have come along and given the owners of these datasets the ability to compute against the datasets privately? is this the secret sauce thatâ€™s only enabled through ocean protocol?  if not  then is it the open  networked and decentralised nature of the ocean protocol? under this assumption we are assuming that an open  networked and decentralised org structure is the superior org structure for executing on this opportunity.Â   it would be great to better understand this topic so that we can more accurately convey the usp to the market. knowing the answer to this should also help indicate where to start looking for new business opportunities with ocean.

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: the secret sauce part with compute to data is one important factor but the other factor that makes ocean standout is the pricing mechanism of the assets. this expands ocean from being a two sided market to much more. the stakers become a part of the market as well. they curate  price and validate datasets but also benefit from that.  the combination of these features makes ocean a ğŸ¦„.  i am very open to have sessions with you and @mark to discuss this further and create an overview and analysis paper.

AUTHOR: Frederic#8800
CONTENT: (damn  robin was already here while i was typing ğŸ˜„ as always ğŸš€ ğŸ‘ğŸ¼ )  hi scott! these are super valuable thoughts. thanks for sharing! the answer includes my personal perspective  there is potentially a lot more  but this is what is important in my opinion:  with compute-to-data you can sell data access without having the problems you mentioned. if set up correctly  there is no â€œbackslashâ€ from customers/business partners/shareholders because the data is never moved  data consumers never see the data itself.  still  you (and any buyer) can generate insights on private data in a fully compliant way. this includes machine learning  business analytics  or other forms of data aggregation. itâ€™s not about the data owner who can compute here. itâ€™s about any potential buyer. and because ocean is permissionless  this could be anyone.  as you say  this is a risk/reward trade-off. and the more sensitive the data  the more security you need to balance the risk.   data monetization makes sense for traditional companies in many cases  even when companies compete. mobi is an example where traditional automakers can potentially share datasets for autonomous driving (without giving away the data) to compete with tesla. in other cases  data can be a â€œbyproductâ€ of a companies core business. in this case  itâ€™s only a cost-center and they could start monetizing it. compared to what is on the market right now  c2d is more about huge and valuable datasets. there are many similar examples we could think of.  â€œturn your data storage into a profit centerâ€ (while keeping ownership and full control and being compliant) is one of the opportunities here.

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: hi @robin | dataunion   @frederic and @kaimeinke thank you for your thoughts.  the pricing mechanism is definitely an interesting feature and one where the incentives that exist would probably be harder to replicate in a private model (in my head i keep comparing this to a private venture  not to discredit the ocean project but to instead uncover the unique benefits of op). staking tokens on datasets encourages market participants to curate good data and send a signal to the market that â€˜this is good dataâ€™ which is great.   open and permissionless access to data for c2d applications to run on is also another great benefit. assuming this means that some people (with good intentions!) are accessing datasets they couldnâ€™t otherwise access through other third party providers already.   data unions and shared data initiatives (like scanning bills and monetising as a group) is also a unique and interesting concept. in theory i could probably start something like that today (as a private venture) but be subject to a number of local laws and regulations (friction) and so doing something like this on op where the incentives are closer to the consumer than they maybe are in a private model could be a unique benefit.

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: thinking these scenarios through is starting to lead me down the path ofâ€¦ maybe the networked  permissionless and incentive based model is a fundamentally superior model for mass scale than a private model. i.e. a private company can only hire so quickly  expand into new markets so quickly and jump on new trends so quickly. in other words it can only spread its incentives so thinly before it runs out.   op (and other decentralised projects for that matter) are more organic and take on a life of their own. as they are open and permissionless  anyone can jump on board  have a go  at no cost to the overarching entity (op) i.e  not many people are spending their spare time thinking up new ways for jeff bezos to grow his empire - he has to employ people to do that for him.   therefore  those that jump on board and build things the market wants are rewarded and those that donâ€™t  simply try again or fade away. the equivalent would be trying to convince a bunch of investors to invest in a private company where we will pay anyone who walks in through the door to do stuff and some will succeed and others will fail but we donâ€™t really know whatâ€™s going to happen. ğŸ˜†   i feel like iâ€™ve either gone on a complete tangent or am touching on something fundamentally important?

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: bruce said at some point that amms and accompanying dexs are already providing a ton of savings as such a service in the traditional finance world would cost 50k+$ - in web3 less than 500$.  the same is true for hiring  payments  authenticating and outreach in the web3 space. wallets and the options that are attached to them are a powerful tool.  i think the savings and the faster verification of ideas is an important point.

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: thanks again @robin | dataunion and @kaimeinke i think this gives me enough to go on for now at least! in terms of next steps it might be worth putting all of this thinking together into a document/blog post and share it here for review before publishing.

CONTENT: good morning @everyone  hope you all had a great we!  â˜€ï¸  quick update to keep you in the loop! ğŸš€   as most of you may have realised from the ambassadors telegram group q4/2021 saw a lot of planning and strategising. the vision of the ambassador program is to build an impactful global team that supports the growth of the ocean protocol ecosystem worldwide and  in order to achieve this  the program needs to be well structured to welcome dozens  if not hundreds  of new ambassadors from each part of the world. ambassadors are now working hard to complete their tasks on time. the new program will be ready by end of this month and today we're sharing what will be its core: a brand new **activity farming and rewards system.**    **activity farming**. this is a list of activities that you as an ambassador can pick from and start working on anytime. https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1r-ng2vjvicg_a3cuk9fph2queaoyzhrwnyzyhvouu4m/edit?usp=sharing once you find the activity you like and you are ready to start  add a trello card with the name of the activity under the â€œactiveâ€ column.    - **rewards system**. we have introduced a mix of basic rewards and performance rewards to promote fairness  transparency  and to incentivise high-quality works.  base rewards are distributed at the end of each month upon meeting the minimum requirements  whilst performance rewards will be distributed upon meeting the predetermined targets at the end of the relevant period.   note:  if you would like to propose an initiative not present in the activity farming list  please add a trello card in the â€œactivities awaiting confirmationâ€ column and share details such as objectives  rewards request  eta. your initiative will then be evaluated by the ap team.   the activity farming list is a living document  it will be reviewed monthly and improved as the program grows. we always welcome suggestions  so please share feedback by adding your comments in the google docs.  happy farming! ğŸ§‘â€ğŸŒ¾ â¤ï¸

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: hi drprk  thanks for sharing the gitbook and the medium article. i've checked them out and would have a few points of feedback: 1)    the gitbook was a great idea  and it looks awesome. the indian program is delivering on its objectives  which is excellent for everyone in the ecosystem! 2)    handling ambassador recruitment through the gitbook makes sense to build a vibrant indian community  but it is not appropriate to recruit â€œocean ambassadorsâ€ in my opinion. why do i say that?  a.    because the ocean ambassadors have nearly completed a revamp of the onboarding process  and once the ambassador website will be up  the gitbook will be redundant. i would personally avoid duplicating processes/adding complexity and potential confusion for new ambassadors.  b.    and because if we use the same process to recruit new members for different groups  we may end up facing unnecessary and unwishful competition across â€˜branchesâ€™ of the program.  c.    finally  it could make sense to consider regional programs as standalone programs  that are not affiliated with the general ambassador group. all would meet and interact in a new outreach wg  which i understand is in the process of being created. thatâ€™d be a great way to federate  share best practices and content  and loosely coordinate across all country programs  including japan  turkey  greece  nigeria  india  ..etc.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: 3)    great article on ocean academy. having workshops on top is indeed helpful. it may need to be updated soon as we fine tune the launch of ocean academy v2  which was planned for end dec â€™21  but will be shipped end jan â€˜22. here is the updated flow and content that iâ€™m currently migrating to github: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rzaz5aa9axjt6ygjgshtigtk9ambl4pdphxud-vjhog/edit?usp=sharing   the content is easier to understand/digest  and is organized in a more logical flow for newcomers. in addition  the front-end + back-end have been updated and will be deployed at the same time as the content  so the user experience will be greatly improved with this v2.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: ocean academy may be further improved  of course. any specific observations  thoughts and feedback are good to take!

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: super thanks for the feedback and for your time that you've taken @lrt ğŸ™Œ   1 & 2) will go through with the feedback with some more considerations. i will also convey them to @andrea | ocean protocol   i had a call earlier today where i expressed that the ambassador 'program' per se will be an effective add-on with funneling mechanisms & remove duplicity  with more focus on managing traffic henceforth. i will work on your feedback and pass onto andrea as well so it's in line with the revamped process.   **but** i see why you mention that they need not be recruited. i will see if the google form can be sunset with a different mechanism in place  adding redundant process can affect the ux of the general program. rebranding it slightly different will be helpful in context of outreach.  c) the outreach wg makes sense  will be a great place to have the processes separate from the ambassador program in general.  3) thanks for the feedback. workshops will be planned in tandem with feedback on the process of v2 version of the academy as well. i will check the updated flow before discussing this again while planning the academy.

AUTHOR: doteth
CONTENT: buongiorno @everyone ğŸ˜ƒ  we are feeling extremely happy to see lot of work coming to fruition. in fact  i am proud to finally announce the official revamp of the ocean protocol ambassador program (opap) ğŸš€   q4/2021 and beginning of q1/2022 has seen a lot of planning  strategising and executing from every single ambassadors. the vision of the ambassador program is to build an impactful global team  that supports the growth of the ocean protocol ecosystem worldwide and  in order to achieve this  the program needs to be well structured to welcome dozens  if not hundreds  of new ambassadors from each part of the world. this may  in the future  also involve having regional communities operating under the opap umbrella.   keeping our vision and needs in mind  the new program restructuring is now complete. i want to thank all ambassadors and ocean core team for their commitment to the program. particularly i want to personally thank @lrt  @robin | dataunion   @blockchainlugano and @zippy1979 for supporting us in making this possible.   today i'm excited to announce:  - a revamped workspace to allow better coordination amongst ambassadors. the workspace is hosted on notion  a tool that promotes team work and transparency. more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/welcome-aboard-cc9dbe2acbf44908aa7e8aa712a2b9f9  - a revamped onboarding process  where candidates will be guided through the ambassador website (work in progress: http://oceanambassadors.community) -> ocean 101 -> and eventually invited to an onboarding video call scheduled each week.  - the introduction of "activity farming". a smooth and efficient process for each ambassador to actively contribute to preapproved activities supporting opf  and get rewarded based on two criteria: the deliverable itself & performance. more details here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1r-ng2vjvicg_a3cuk9fph2queaoyzhrwnyzyhvouu4m/edit?usp=sharing  - an experimental reputation system that helps to promote engagement  increased contributions and team working within the opap. this system allows ambassadors to earn xp based on their contribution to the program - helping them stand out in our new ambassador leaderboard. more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/leaderboard-f24b2461b60f4ce1970b255f7dd8767f  - oceanacropolis. an open space for each ambassador to showcase their work  giving them (and everyone else) visibility across social media channels such as twitter. more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/oceanacropolis-750c110a7a234a7e86f577e7431f573c  - a revised reward system to promote fairness  transparency  and to incentivise high-quality work. we have introduced a mix of basic rewards and performance rewards. again  more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/ocean-rewards-e803515ecda54c1f8fa5200af0343d40  - an open calendar where to find all opap meetings. as agreed with @idiom | ocean protocol  all future ambassadors meetings going forward will be publicly held in the #ambassadors wg. more details here: https://www.notion.so/oceanambassadors/ff179fec09014037b29ac1bce067080a?v=47d781c17e0e426cafc48623f9398688  - an awesome video for everyone to quickly learn about ocean protocol and familiarise with the data economy. sneak peek coming asap.   last but not least  we have also been working on our first ambassadordao. however  this is still work in progress and shanâ€™t reveal more at this time ğŸ¤   plenty more is in the pipeline  and we're all looking forward to seeing what 2022 has for us!  #theyearofadoption  happy farming! ğŸ‘©â€ğŸŒ¾ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸŒ¾ â¤ï¸   andrea

CONTENT: i read their whitepaper - it somehow lets people retain their annotations as nfts. but i am very technical and really did not understand how and why that should work. this looks like a lot of marketing for me.  i also do not at all understand why a project that a co-founder of ocean invested in makes it into the ocean protocol news stream. there is no endorsement of ocean protocol and ocean also does not appear anywhere in their whitepaper or technical specs.  nonetheless this is interesting to see as it is very similar to what we are building with dataunion  we just have a different approach ğŸ™‚ so far they have 0 p2e games  this is just marketing.

CONTENT: it is kind of a data union around nlp data  so this is amazing from my point of view ğŸ™‚ but i am also not convinced yet of solana but my developers told me about it/held it when it was at 5$. should have listened to them back then.

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: my 2 ocean on the discussion (or do we have a 'cent' version of ocean yet?)  starting off with a general funda (feel free to critique).  for a p2e concept to work on the current concept  and to interface with a convenient crypto-network component it has to be with a chain that doesn't disturb the end-user in anyway right?  so essentially that has to function with a network that is conducive for faster txns and lower fee  so from my birds eye view i see that polygon  solana are really popular on that front ~ which has happened as a result of marketing of course. might be a reason why we have so many p2e games from a few suspect chains as a function of marketing/ecosystem push.  do you have any line of thoughts to this @robin | dataunion on what you're developing?

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: yeah  we are going to work with polygon as we are using ocean protocol tech. but also looking at celo (mobile first proof of stake  eco friendly chain) and everything else where ocean protocol is available (e.g. kusama  polkadot via moonbeam). we are suffering from having our pool on ethereum mainnet for a long time now and will change that very soon when v4 comes out ğŸ™‚

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: cool that's great to know. so i suppose at the end of the day when you're thinking of p2e project you'd only be looking at how users engage or would that be something that has to be very exclusive from a particular ecosystem

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: no  in the end it is important that they have an identity in the form of a wallet or a ssi identity but also the option to receive part of the value being created from the p2e project they are participating in. so we could have chains connected where there is no data asset being offered but the value created is just transfered there from another chain. and our backend is very flexible in regard to the identification scheme used.

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: ah i see. so the p2e element would be web3 specific nonetheless? or if a person has an ssi identity that is agnostic to web3 products  can they still participate in your p2e product?

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: don't mind me if you think this is a lot of questions. i'm just curious on some alphas and to learn something new ğŸ˜„

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: it is important that this person can be identified to make the e part of p2e available to them - a wallet is a great piece of technology that enables that ğŸ™‚ but where that is possible/can be depends on where the value is created. in dataunion's case - where is the data being offered via compute-to-data and where are the algorithms being used? that is where the value is created and this value is then split to the participants and made available to their ssi/wallet identity.

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: alright that makes sense. from the overall funda  it's so commendable to see that we have a p2e within our ecosystem that is evolving to be chain-agnostic (courtesy ocean-stack) and web3 native. not a lot of people try to start off with that. i know manan is also working on oceanverse game so looking forward to both.

AUTHOR: doteth

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: the first article is spot on imo - governance minimization is key. i believe they overstate "consensus" which relates to day-to-day operations and understate "strategic governance" which relates to deep gov redesign  vision or objective changes of the systems when needed.   the gitcoin presentation is fascinating. i wish someone old these guys that data should be expressed in % terms rather than absolute number of survey respondents.. but it doesn't change the value of the insights gathered. brilliant. i think we can relate to this comment re pain points "the biggest pain point are people who want to help but need to be helped to be able to help ğŸ™‚ so  for now only very assertive people find something to do."

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: the fei protocol article provides some interesting thoughts on a particular implementation of "optimistic governance". our intended implementation in "activity farming" is more flat  and is handled "after-the-facts"   this means that ***requests for $ocean rewards are made by the ambassador working on an activity only once the activity has been delivered or once the activity performance can be attested. activities do not need to be pre-aligned*** prior to working on them  as long as they are in our activity farming list  and the deliverable complies with our ambassador pledge.  upon submission  ***by default activities are approved and paid***. if another ambassador has doubts and wants to review the activity  the reviewing ambassador should state so  which will trigger a review process in which ambassadors should discuss and conclude whether the activity should be paid or not.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: more on optimistic governance: https://docs.gyro.finance/governance/primitives/optimistic-approval and https://ournetwork.substack.com/p/our-network-deep-dive-2 --- this is all based on web3 stacks  but we could learn faster by handling things off-chain  iterating fast to learn and implementing on-chain when a solution makes sense.   we don't really have much to fear about gev exploits as we will most likely never have deep pockets  and our purpose is not monetary. but of course we want to avoid as many obvious flaws in our governance processes as possible

CONTENT: hi ambassador - i made a proposal to change the reward structure for translation articles and put it into activity farming at the moment its 30$ base reward for articles > 500 words and 1000$ base reward for articles > 1000 words.   the problem is : the most interesting and relevant articles from op are mainly above 1500 - 2000 words. but at the moment the work/reward ratio for articles slightly above 1000 words is the best. so the motivation to translate that kind of articles instead of the ones that are much more interesting & relevant is much higher. by raising the reward for this the motivation to translate that articles will rise.   i suggest adding 3 categories according to the work load:   > 1500 words = 150 usd base rewards + 450 usd bonus rewards for 1k impressions within 3 month > 2000 words = 200 usd base rewards + 600 usd bonus rewards for 1k impressions within 3 month > 2500 words = 250 usd base rewards + 750 usd bonus rewards for 1k impressions within 3 month

AUTHOR: doteth
CONTENT: ğŸ“š  **easy poll - quick guide** ğŸ“š   - with the /poll command you can easily create polls. normal polls have no time limit. a poll can be either a simple yes/no poll or a poll with up to 20 custom answers. when you create a poll  you can choose who is allowed to vote  - with the /timepoll command you can easily create polls with time limit. in this case a poll can run for a maximum of 7 days.  **useful commands to use: **  allowedrole - to restrict voting to certain roles  text - to add a long description  perhaps to give context and introduce the reason of the poll time - to set a time limit to the poll  **note:**  - you can only create a poll if you're an admin  or have been given the pollcreator role - to create polls in private channels  go to channel -> permissions -> add role -> easypoll

CONTENT: hi @kitblake i will focus on the first point for now. storytelling. i understand the concept. the story is interestingly told. maybe the comic will be interesting? there is a lot of action. one question. why is the main character's name volodymyr?    if you create a text and publish it at a certain time and under certain circumstances. readers will always have connotations of what is happening around them. i suggest choosing a more neutral name for these times. so that readers can fully focus on your story without context. contexts create metaphors.

AUTHOR: kitblake
CONTENT: @igor k and @zamirana  thanks for your reactions! i see now that giving the main character the same first name as the ukrainian president may not have been amusing and proved a distraction. so iâ€™ve changed the name. but i havenâ€™t used alice or bob. hereâ€™s the thinking.  that wikipedia article was illuminating. i wasnâ€™t thrilled with alice or bob because they have personalities. now iâ€™ve learned that their personalities were defined in an "after dinner speech" in 1984. the main character of our user story doesnâ€™t fit those personalities. heâ€™s a developer type.  since those early days more characters have been added to the alice & bob story. thereâ€™s eve  whoâ€™s an eavesdropper  and mallory  whoâ€™s malicious. thereâ€™s also â€œivan the honourableâ€ who was invented in 2002.  'ivan' is a fitting name for a dev. it connotes the right mindset. someone whoâ€™s honourable and concerned about the quality of the code. the name is also not tied to any specific country. could even be american  like alice & bob are.  thus the main character in our user story is now ivan  and i think itâ€™s a real improvement. thanks for your feedback  it proved valuable. ğŸ™

CONTENT: ok team  we took  time to go through the bounties delivered last week. really chewed on this which is why today is wednesday and normally this is done by monday  but i am remaining shellshocked that 95% of the work put in is simply incorrect or incoherent  some on a large scale. none of you will win bounties this way  so imo really read and ask questions to understand how this works  or you will be wasting your precious time for zero reward:  here is an example  see if you can spot an issue  and this is taken from the top 2 threads submitted (good job btw  because it is nearly there!).  part of a posted thread:  ocean templates is an open-source toolkit from @oceanprotocol that provides a complete answer to common issues experienced in #blockchain dapp development.   reasoning this is not of useable quality:  ocean protocol does provide a set of tools and infrastructure to help developers build decentralized applications (dapps) centered around data marketplaces. this includes the usage of templates that *facilitate* standardized data exchange agreements.  however  it's important to note that ocean protocol and its tools are specifically tailored to data sharing  buying  and selling use-cases. they may not address all the "common issues" experienced in general blockchain dapp development  but they do indeed provide significant benefits for those particular use-cases.  with that in mind  a more accurate statement might be:  ocean templates  part of the @oceanprotocol toolkit  provides a comprehensive solution to common challenges experienced in blockchain-based data marketplace development. this thread will inform developers how it can reduce complications and accelerate time-to-market for developing data-centric dapps.  :opapshield: **always be sure to research the specific functionalities and scope of a particular toolkit or platform before making broad claims about its applicability and benefits.**

AUTHOR: beason82
CONTENT: i have a friend who works in data protection who says this is incorrect:  "so it's 'special category data' that's afforded extra protection and where the data is 'stored' is irrelevant  it's where it is 'processed'. also gdpr doesn't require data to stay on 'european soil'  gdpr applies to the 'eu' and there are jurisdictions which are afforded 'adequacy' that are outside of the 'eu'. there are circumstances where you could transfer special category data outside of the eu if you have the appropriate mechanisms in place"

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: do you think ocean protocol's partnership with moonbeam has had much of an impact? @ambassador   my thoughts on it:   the collaboration with moonbeam network signifies ocean protocol's expansion to the polkadot blockchain. initial integration will empower users to seamlessly "publish  stake  and buy" data within polkadot's ecosystem. assets from both ethereum mainnet and moonbeam will eventually coexist within the ocean market  a platform for data discovery and exchange. enhanced privacy features  network bridging  and liquidity sharing are also on the horizon.  trent mcconaghy  co-founder of ocean protocol  highlights the alignment of ocean's multi-blockchain vision with polkadot's interoperability focus. moonbeam's ethereum compatibility makes it a logical starting point for ocean's polkadot venture.   the moonbeam team is constantly working to simplify the implementation process for ethereum developers who want to migrate to polkadot. ocean protocol chose moonbeam as an extension point because of its unrivaled compatibility. the ocean team can now utilize their existing ethereum smart contracts to access the new and growing polkadot ecosystem.

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: also wanted to get on the topic of utu's ai-driven trust infrastructure with ocean ones   utu's ai-driven trust infrastructure will assimilate data providers  consumers  datasets  and entities' interactions to construct comprehensive trust profiles. moreover  ocean users can rate and review these entities  all contributing to a dynamically analyzed trust signal.  this approach elevates trust and transparency within ocean market  minimizing transactional friction. users can seamlessly access quality datasets from reliable providers  utilize data for analysis or stake  and avoid risks like rug pulls  fostering a more secure and reliable ecosystem  furthermore  the utu protocol rewards users for providing precise ratings and reviews while safeguarding their data privacy. collaborating with ocean will streamline the process for utu users to monetize their data on ocean market as data providers. users retain complete authority over shared data  deciding which to monetize and its usage terms.  the partnership aims to facilitate data exchange between their protocols. this entails incorporating publicly-available  on-chain utu data like endorsements into ocean market  procuring relevant ocean market datasets for the utu protocol  and analyzing datasets to generate utu recommendations and insights.

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: i think  the collaboration between ocean protocol and moonbeam is important. it helps ocean protocol become part of another blockchain. it gives people more ways to work with data. it also allows them to make bets based on that data. all in all  these are new opportunities for ocean protocol. working with utu is also a good thing. they are using artificial intelligence to help people trust each other when sharing data. so ocean market becomes a place to find safe and quality data. and utu helps users make money from their data on ocean market.
